Certainly! Below is a script that formats the provided content into a form which accepts and saves user-inputted text. This script uses HTML and JavaScript to create an interactive form where users can input text for different sections and save the content.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Heartland Institute Communication Form</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .form-container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: auto;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
        textarea {
            width: 100%;
            height: 100px;
            margin-top: 5px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="form-container">
    <h1>Heartland Institute Communication Form</h1>

    <form id="communicationForm">
        <label for="pressRelease">Press Release:</label>
        <textarea id="pressRelease" name="pressRelease"></textarea>

        <label for="opEd">Op-Ed:</label>
        <textarea id="opEd" name="opEd"></textarea>

        <label for="socialMediaPost">Social Media Post:</label>
        <textarea id="socialMediaPost" name="socialMediaPost"></textarea>

        <label for="blogPost">Blog Post:</label>
        <textarea id="blogPost" name="blogPost"></textarea>

        <label for="eventAnnouncement">Event Announcement:</label>
        <textarea id="eventAnnouncement" name="eventAnnouncement"></textarea>

        <button type="submit">Save and Submit</button>
    </form>

    <div id="output"></div>
</div>

<script>
    document.getElementById('communicationForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
        event.preventDefault();

        const pressRelease = document.getElementById('pressRelease').value;
        const opEd = document.getElementById('opEd').value;
        const socialMediaPost = document.getElementById('socialMediaPost').value;
        const blogPost = document.getElementById('blogPost').value;
        const eventAnnouncement = document.getElementById('eventAnnouncement').value;

        const output = `
            <h2>Press Release:</h2>
            <p>${pressRelease}</p>

            <h2>Op-Ed:</h2>
            <p>${opEd}</p>

            <h2>Social Media Post:</h2>
            <p>${socialMediaPost}</p>

            <h2>Blog Post:</h2>
            <p>${blogPost}</p>

            <h2>Event Announcement:</h2>
            <p>${eventAnnouncement}</p>
        `;

        document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = output;
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**:
    - The form contains five textareas for different types of content (Press Release, Op-Ed, Social Media Post, Blog Post, and Event Announcement).
    - Each textarea has a unique ID and name attribute.
    - A submit button is included to trigger the form submission.

2. **CSS Styling**:
    - Basic styling is applied to make the form visually appealing and easy to use.

3. **JavaScript Functionality**:
    - An event listener is added to the form to handle the `submit` event.
    - When the form is submitted, the event is prevented from default behavior.
    - The values from each textarea are retrieved and stored in variables.
    - The content is formatted and displayed in a `<div>` element with the ID `output`.

This script allows users to input and save different types of communication content, which is then displayed on the page for review.

